body:
Ok before someone  jumps to say I'm wrong, and this is not a bug or whatever, I want to make clear I have no fucking idea if it's intended to do what it should or not, I didn't even try them, but those locks really look suspicious... so... yes it's not a bug (at least yet) just suspicious code.

So I was taking a look at the session_redis_driver and session_memcached_driver when I noticed something... weird.

The relevant part of the code is the _get_lock() function on both drivers, what they do is something similar to that:

``` PHP
protected function _get_lock($session_id)
    {
        if (isset($this->_lock_key))
        {
            return $this->_memcached->replace($this->_lock_key, time(), 5); // memcached
            return $this->_redis->setTimeout($this->_lock_key, 5); // redis
        }

        // [code #1 to try to aquire the lock]
        // If it succeeds set _lock_key and return true
        // If it didn't succeed (the lock is taken) continue

        // [code #2 to try to aquire the lock]
                // Try #2 a few times and if success do something similar to 1 (particullary set _lock_key)
        // If it didn't succeed for those few times fail.
    }
```

And the possible break is: At time 0, we receive the first request, the database is empty so it just aquires the lock from code#1 and returns, but let's imagine this request, is a big computing that will take exactly 7 seconds.

Now at time 3, we receive another request (while the other process is still computing the past request), there's still the lock in the database so we execute code#2 for around 2 seconds, and finally receive the lock. 

At time 7, the first request, finishes the computing and decides to store it on session cause it's convinient...
so it goes to the _get_lock function and since this process had already accessed the session before, he already has the _lock_key "set" enters the if and bam... now both request have access to the session...

Ok, now I admit I don't know really good (in fact not at all) the redis and memcached drivers, and also don't know if this is solved behind the scenes with something weird as clearing _lock_key every 5 seconds or so, but to me it looks bugful. (Or maybe I missed something, in which case a simple explanation would make the deal)
